Collected Data Quality Measures

This section includes metrics representing the quality of the EEG data.

Flatline channel metric

The flat-line channels are indicated with red circles. Channels exhibiting flat-lines are identified by having a near-constant signal value possibly with signal quantization noise for an extended period of time, here by default 5 or more seconds consecutive. Such channels most likely indicate sensors becoming temporarily disconnected.

Channel drop-out proportion

This quantitative measure indicates the level of data quality for each channel, the darker and bigger disks have lower quality. The metric quantifies the fraction of time during the session during which the channel becomes less correlated to its neighbors than a fixed threshold. The correlation is measured robustly using a RANSAC estimator.

High frequency noise level score

This is a quantitative measure indicating the level of high frequency noise, darker and bigger disks indicate channels with higher noise level. The metric displays the ratio of power in the high-frequency band (50Hz+) over the power in the EEG-frequency band, quantified in z-scores relative to the robust population mean across all channels (population standard deviation also robustly estimated). A high score could indicate significant muscle artifact, poor electrode conductivity, or electromagnetic interference.

Bad channel classification metric

Red circles indicate bad channels and green circles indicate good channels. The bad-channel detection metric combines the correlation measure and high-frequency noise measures into a combined metric and applies a binary classification into good vs bad channels.

Average correlation to neighboring channels

This quantitative measure indicates the average correlation between channel signals and a robustly estimated surrogate channel signal derived from neighboring channels. Larger and greener disks indicate channels that are more highly correlated with other channels (indicating higher quality). Smaller and redder disks indicate channels that have lower correlation and may be compromised.

Artifact to clean EEG ratio

This quantitative measure indicates the prevalence of artifacts in each channel previously labeled as good, the channels with darker and bigger disks have higher artifact level. The metric quantifies the ratio of amplitude of artifacts relative to the clean EEG amplitude.

Line noise to raw EEG ratio

This quantitative measure indicates the level of line noise on each channel, the channels with darker and bigger disks have higher level of line noise. This metric quantifies the variance explained by line noise in the 55-65Hz band, after 1/f correction.

Event-Related Potential Analysis

Number of trials retained/averaged over: correct: 192, incorrect: 133

ERPimages

This section shows ERPimages for selected channels. An ERPimage is a raster plot where each row shows the event-locked time-varying channel potential for a single trial. Below each ERPimage is plotted the trial-averaged event-related potential (ERP). Note this is simply the average of the rows of the ERPimage.

Mean ERPs

This section plots ERPs for selected channels. Channel traces can be toggled on and off by clicking on the colored square next to the channel label in the legend. The average voltage in the interval prior to the event is used as the baseline for ERP calculation.

Power Spectral Analysis

Number of trials retained/averaged over: correct: 192, incorrect: 133

ERSP

Below is the event-related spectral perturbation (ERSP) for selected channels. The ERSP shows the change in power (averaged over event-locked trials) at each frequency, relative to the pre-event baseline window. The units of measurement are decibels.

Average Power Spectra

Plots showing average spectral density for all ERPs, by channel and by region of interest.

Connectivity Analysis

This section shows the event-related connectivity matrix (multivariate spectral Granger Causality) between selected cortical regions of interest following sLORETA source localization, averaged over all trials within each condition. The matrices show the change in connectivity from the pre-event baseline, averaged within the 2-8Hz frequency band (delta-theta) over the interval of 0.1 to 0.4 sec following the event. The direction of causal information transfer is from columns to rows. Warm colors indicate increased causal information transfer between a pair of ROIs, while cool colors indicate decreased causal information transfer.
